abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: Founded in 1995, Collective: Unconscious (C:U) was an experimental theater group strongly committed to the neighborhood of Manhattan's Lower East Side and its developing artists. Collective: Unconscious members staged dozens of their own productions at the group's home on Ludlow Street (and later on Church Street) and rented space to many other performers. As leaders of other performance groups, Collective members also involved Collective: Unconscious in many of the downtown cultural festivals of the 1990s and early 2000s, including the New York International Fringe Festival and the Downtown Arts Festival. The materials in the collection document the production and promotion of performances staged and hosted by the Collective and contains exhaustive documentation of the group's administrative functions and financial difficulties.

p.value: Open to researchers. Restrictions include two folders in Series II: Financial. Series IIA contains the folder “Brian Homa personal” which includes a transcript which may be viewed only by Brian Homa. Series IIC contains the folder "Tax forms, Daniel E. Series I: Production Files is comprised of paper archives that relate to Collective: Unconscious’s production of theatrical events. This series includes scripts for individual plays and festivals, proposals, publicity, and miscellaneous papers associated with the general production of artistic forms and materials relating to the rental of performance space. Series II: Administrative Files includes documents relating to building maintenance, day-to-day operations and communication. Extensive billing records and itemized receipts from multiple operating years are also included. This series also contains meeting minutes, financial records, tax returns and grant paperwork. Among the financial records are copies of the group’s leases and lengthy correspondence with both landlords and attorneys over issues and disputes. Of particular interest are folders relevant to the lease and to insurance, which document the increasing cost of rental and fire insurance in a Lower East Side neighborhood in a state of rapid change after 9/11.
